TEACHER.observations:
I think that for some of the maps it is (maybe by design and maybe not) entirely possible to pass with perfect score just by luck and some amount of learning.

It is very hard to have any signals that are not mimicking, as for signals to arise we need to somehow pre-determine some sort of rules which we are workin on. Especially in the setting of only visual signals, it seems impossible to me to know when the signal ends and when the new one starts, as opposed to, for example, prefix codes which are written signals. Even in those encodings there is some pre-determined notion on what is going to be used. However, we did manage to get some basic signals such as shapes that need to be touched. 

It is possible to pass many maps just by mimicking. However, for this to work, one needs to have a large amount of initial shapes and data, for other person to be able to distinguish from different strategies that overlap at different times.

But it was a very interesting experience that illuminated how are we able to transfer information in such a medium.
